---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import {mutatorSidebar} from '../../../data/mutator-sidebar';
import {Code} from 'astro:components';
---

<DocsLayout title="Sealed Classes" sidebar={mutatorSidebar}
            description="Polymorphic mutation with sealed interfaces, cast(), and filterMutatorsOf">

    <h1>Sealed Classes</h1>

    <p class="text-xl text-gray-400 !mt-2 !mb-8">
        Mutate polymorphic hierarchies with <code>cast()</code> for individual elements
        and <code>filterMutatorsOf&lt;T&gt;()</code> for typed collection access.
    </p>

    <h2>Defining a sealed hierarchy</h2>

    <p>Annotate the sealed interface (or sealed class) with <code>@Mutable</code>. The subtypes don't need separate
        annotations — KSP generates mutators for the entire hierarchy:</p>

    <Code code={`@Mutable
sealed interface PaymentMethod {
    data class CreditCard(
        val number: String,
        val expiry: String,
    ) : PaymentMethod

    data class BankTransfer(
        val iban: String,
        val bic: String,
    ) : PaymentMethod
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Mutating with cast()</h2>

    <p>When you have a <code>Mutator&lt;PaymentMethod&gt;</code>, you don't know the concrete type at compile time. Use
        <code>cast()</code> to narrow the type and mutate:</p>

    <Code code={`val methods: List<PaymentMethod> = listOf(
    PaymentMethod.CreditCard("4111-1111-1111-1111", "12/25"),
    PaymentMethod.BankTransfer("DE89370400440532013000", "COBADEFFXXX"),
)

val updated = methods.mutate {
    forEach { mutator ->
        when (val value = mutator()) {
            is PaymentMethod.CreditCard ->
                mutator.cast(value) { expiry = "12/28" }

            is PaymentMethod.BankTransfer ->
                mutator.cast(value) { bic = "NEWBICXXX" }
        }
    }
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>The <code>cast(value)</code> call narrows the mutator's type parameter. Inside the lambda, you get typed property
        access — <code>expiry</code>, <code>bic</code>, etc. — with full IDE completion and compile-time safety.</p>

    <h2>Filtering with filterMutatorsOf&lt;T&gt;()</h2>

    <p>For <code>ListMutator</code> and <code>SetMutator</code> of sealed types, KSP generates <code>filterMutatorsOf&lt;T&gt;()</code>.
        This returns only the mutators whose underlying value matches the specified subtype:</p>

    <Code code={`val methods: List<PaymentMethod> = listOf(
    PaymentMethod.CreditCard("4111-1111-1111-1111", "12/25"),
    PaymentMethod.BankTransfer("DE89...", "COBADEFFXXX"),
    PaymentMethod.CreditCard("5500-0000-0000-0004", "06/26"),
)

val mutator = methods.mutator()

// Get only the credit card mutators — fully typed as Mutator<CreditCard>
val cards = mutator.filterMutatorsOf<PaymentMethod.CreditCard>()

cards.forEach { cardMutator ->
    cardMutator.expiry = "12/30"  // Typed access — no cast needed
}`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Indexed iteration with cast()</h2>

    <p>You can use <code>forEachIndexed</code> with sealed types just as you'd expect:</p>

    <Code code={`val items: List<SealedInterface> = listOf(
    SealedInterface.One("hello"),
    SealedInterface.Two(42),
)

val updated = items.mutate {
    forEachIndexed { index, mutator ->
        when (val v = mutator()) {
            is SealedInterface.One -> mutator.cast(v) { value += "-${'$'}index" }
            is SealedInterface.Two -> mutator.cast(v) { value += index }
        }
    }
}
// Result: [One("hello-0"), Two(43)]`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <h2>Generated code for sealed types</h2>

    <p>For a <code>@Mutable sealed interface</code>, KSP generates the same <code>.mutator()</code>,
        <code>.mutate {'{ }'}</code>, and collection extensions as for data classes. It additionally generates <code>filterMutatorsOf</code>
        for <code>ListMutator</code> and <code>SetMutator</code>:</p>

    <Code code={`// Generated for List<PaymentMethod>:
inline fun <reified X : PaymentMethod>
    ListMutator<PaymentMethod>.filterMutatorsOf(): List<Mutator<X>>

// Generated for Set<PaymentMethod>:
inline fun <reified X : PaymentMethod>
    SetMutator<PaymentMethod>.filterMutatorsOf(): List<Mutator<X>>`} lang="kotlin" theme="vitesse-dark"/>

    <p>Each subtype also gets its own property accessors, so <code>Mutator&lt;CreditCard&gt;.number</code> and <code>Mutator&lt;BankTransfer&gt;.iban</code>
        are fully typed.</p>

    <div class="not-prose mt-8 flex gap-4">
        <a href="/ultra/mutator/examples"
           class="inline-flex items-center px-6 py-3 bg-brand-600 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-brand-500 transition-colors">
            Real-world examples &rarr;
        </a>
    </div>

</DocsLayout>
